  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "2984750c-f3ba-80b5-915b-e58f2851e3a6",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Recommender System Type",
          "Target of Recommendation",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Initialization Method",
          "Updates to Recommendations",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Recommendation types",
          "Evaluation",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Content-Based Fiiltering",
          "Learning path recommender",
          "144 Mooshak learners, 61 Enki learners for offline evaluation\n\n32 learners for Online evaluation",
          "1 C programming course",
          "LMS logs, Course Metadata, Available Time\n",
          "Users select a lesson as their starting point. Since there is an hierarchy between different lessons - authors assume that if the starting point is X, the learner is already familiar with the pre-requisites of X. \n\n",
          "Paths are adapted lesson by lesson according to the learner’s performance: if the user score is below expectation, auxiliary Learning Objects (LOs) are added; otherwise, the next lesson is recommended.",
          "LO-level interactions (time and score) are clustered using K-Means to compute average or median time and score estimates (Clust.Mean and Clust.Median). Features include time spent, completion rate, and visit frequency. ",
          "Lesson-based learning paths with auxiliary recommendations for weakly mastered lessons.",
          "Enki-Offline\n{MAE: 0.1 - Clust.Mean at Window Size 5, Time: 9 seconds - IRT-3PL at window size 9}\n\nMooshak-Offline\n{MAE: 0.1 - Median at Window Size 9, Time: 9 seconds - Median at window size 2}\n\nOnline\n{Time Spent on Lesson: Experimental Grooup is Substantially Lower, Sum of Scores: Experimental Group is Substantially Higher}",
          "Authors use 2 approaches at building a Recommender System: \n\n1. Depth-First Search on Course Generation from all LO sequences - it allows the learners to follow a path, but often fail to get to the end within the available time.\n\n2. A lesson-based method based on a 2-layered course graph. \n\nAuxiliary LOs are used when learners fail to meet estimated performance.  Experimental group outperformed control in lesson completion and time efficiency but not significantly in final exam scores.\n\nMatrix Factorization and IRT models were also compared for benchmarking.",
          "- Small datasets for offline experiments.  \n- Limited number of participants (n=32) in live evaluation.  \n- Cold-start issue when insufficient data to estimate time/score. \n - Scalability and evaluation framework not validated on large datasets.  - Some over/underestimation of score predictions."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
